<h1>LG Dryer d80, d90, d95 — What the Flow Sense Error Means and How to Fix It</h1>

<p>If your LG dryer is displaying d80, d90, or d95 on the control panel — or showing a "Flow Sense" warning — the dryer's built-in airflow sensor has detected a blockage in the exhaust vent system. These aren't arbitrary fault codes. d80 means 80% restricted, d90 means 90%, d95 means 95%. The dryer is measuring real airflow reduction and warning you before something worse happens. About half the time when we arrive, the vent cleaning alone resolves everything and the customer pays $150–200. The other half of the time the thermal fuse has already blown from the restriction running unchecked, and we're doing both the vent cleaning and the fuse replacement at the same visit. We handle these calls every day across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County — dryers in interior laundry rooms with longer vent runs in Torrance and Glendale get these codes more often than anywhere else.</p>

<h2>What the Codes Mean — and Why the Number Matters</h2>
<p><strong>d80</strong> — 80% restriction. The dryer is still running but heat is building up inside. Clothes take longer to dry, the machine runs hotter than normal, and the laundry room feels humid. This is the warning stage — the vent needs to be cleared but the dryer hasn't shut itself down yet. Lint doesn't move backwards on its own. Don't ignore d80 thinking it'll clear itself.</p>
<p><strong>d90</strong> — 90% restriction. The dryer is reducing heat output as a protective measure. Significantly longer dry times, cabinet getting hot to touch, machine struggling to complete cycles. The thermal fuse is now at real risk of blowing. We've had calls in Pasadena and Burbank where customers ran their dryer for weeks at d90 — by the time we arrived the fuse had blown on top of the vent blockage. Two problems instead of one.</p>
<p><strong>d95</strong> — 95% restriction. Stop immediately. At this level, heat has almost nowhere to go. If you run another heated cycle, the thermal fuse will very likely blow — turning a $150 vent cleaning into a $280–350 fuse replacement on top of it.</p>
<p><strong>Flow Sense warning (no specific code)</strong> — Some older LG models display a general "Flow Sense" warning without a percentage. Treat it the same as d80 — the dryer has detected reduced airflow and needs the vent cleared.</p>

<h2>Why LG Dryers Have the Flow Sense System</h2>
<p>LG was one of the first appliance manufacturers to build airflow monitoring into residential dryers. The Flow Sense system uses internal sensors to measure exhaust velocity and temperature at the blower. When airflow drops below threshold, it calculates the restriction percentage and displays the code. It's a genuinely useful safety feature — it catches vent problems before they blow the thermal fuse or before lint ignites from the heat buildup.</p>
<p>The system is more sensitive than people expect. A vent that looks clear from the outside can still read d80 because the restriction is in the middle of the duct run, around a bend, or at a section of flexible ducting that has kinked or collapsed. We use a calibrated anemometer to measure actual airflow at the exterior vent cap — not just visual inspection — because that's the only way to confirm the restriction is actually cleared. On longer vent runs we also use duct inspection cameras to locate the blockage precisely before we start clearing from either end.</p>

<h2>Where the Blockage Usually Is</h2>
<p><strong>Lint accumulation in the duct</strong> — the most common cause. Lint builds up gradually at every bend and transition fitting. In Calabasas and Malibu homes with longer vent runs and multiple 90-degree bends, lint accumulates faster than in apartments with short straight runs.</p>
<p><strong>Collapsed or kinked flexible duct</strong> — the accordion-style flexible duct behind many dryers gets pushed against the wall over time and kinks, reducing airflow without any lint involved at all. We see this constantly in apartments in Irvine and Newport Beach where the dryer gets pushed tight into its alcove.</p>
<p><strong>Blocked exterior vent cap</strong> — the cap on the outside of the house can jam with lint, a bird nest, or debris. From the inside everything looks fine. We check the exterior cap on every Flow Sense call.</p>
<p><strong>Improper duct material</strong> — thin foil accordion duct crushes and kinks easily and collects lint at every ridge. Building code requires smooth rigid or semi-rigid metal duct for dryer vents. If your installation uses foil accordion duct and you're getting recurring Flow Sense codes, the duct may need to be replaced rather than just cleaned — and we can do that on the same visit in most cases.</p>

<h2>What We Do On-Site</h2>
<p>We start by measuring actual airflow at the exterior vent cap while the dryer runs — this tells us immediately how severe the restriction is. Then we clear the blockage working from both ends of the vent run. After clearing, we remeasure to confirm the code won't come back. We also check the flexible duct behind the dryer for kinks and the exterior cap for damage. And we test the thermal fuse — if the dryer has been running at d90 or d95 for a while, the fuse may be on its way out or already blown. Better to know now than to have the customer call back a week later because the dryer still won't heat.</p>
<p>A failing Flow Sense sensor can also mask <a href="/symptoms/lg-dryer-not-heating/">heating issues</a> that need simultaneous attention — we check for that too while we're on-site. Total time: 45–75 minutes for a standard vent clearing. Longer runs or installations needing duct replacement take more time.</p>

<h2>When the Code Returns After Clearing</h2>
<p>If d80 or d90 comes back within a few loads after we clear the vent, two possibilities. First: the duct material is the problem — foil accordion duct that's partially collapsed can't be fully cleared, it needs to be replaced with rigid metal. Second: the Flow Sense thermistor sensor is reading incorrectly even when the vent is clear — less common but we see it on older DLGX models. We test the thermistor on callbacks and identify which scenario it is.</p>

<h2>What It Costs</h2>
<p>Vent cleaning and clearing: <strong>$150–200</strong> for most installations — and about 50% of Flow Sense calls end right here. If the thermal fuse has already blown from the restriction, we add fuse replacement at the same visit: $280–350. Total for both: $350–450. If the duct needs to be replaced with proper rigid metal, we quote that on-site based on the length and routing.</p>
<p>Overall range for Flow Sense calls: <strong>$150–350</strong>. The $65 diagnostic fee is waived when you approve any repair. Written quote after diagnosis, before we start anything.</p>
<p>Every invoice includes a 10% discount code for your next service call — never expires, applies to any LG dryer repair at your home.</p>

<h2>How to Reduce Future Blockages</h2>
<p>Clean the lint filter before every load. Check the exterior vent cap monthly while the dryer runs — confirm you feel strong airflow. Have the vent professionally cleaned every 1–2 years if you use the dryer daily. If your installation uses flexible foil duct, strongly consider having it replaced with semi-rigid metal — it lasts longer, collects less lint, and won't collapse. And if you see d80, treat it as urgent. Don't wait for d95.</p>

