<h2>Questions We Get on These Calls</h2>

<h3>My LG dryer shows d80 — can I keep using it?</h3>
<p>You can run it, but you're putting the thermal fuse at risk with every cycle. At d80 the vent is 80% blocked and heat is building up inside. The longer you run it, the more likely the fuse blows — turning a $150 vent cleaning into a $280–350 fuse replacement plus the cleaning. Clear the vent first.</p>

<h3>My LG dryer shows d90 or d95 — is it safe to use?</h3>
<p>At d90 we strongly recommend stopping heated cycles. At d95, stop immediately — the thermal fuse is very likely to blow on the next cycle. Call us for same-day vent clearing.</p>

<h3>I cleaned the lint trap but d80 is still showing. Why?</h3>
<p>The lint trap catches most lint but not all — the rest accumulates in the duct over time. The d80 code means the duct itself is blocked, not just the trap. The blockage is somewhere between the back of the dryer and the exterior vent cap and needs to be physically cleared.</p>

<h3>Can I fix the d80 code myself?</h3>
<p>Basic cleaning from both ends with a dryer vent cleaning kit sometimes works on short straight vent runs. If the run is long, has multiple bends, or the blockage is in the middle of the duct, DIY cleaning often doesn't fully clear it — and the code comes back within a few loads. We use an anemometer to verify actual airflow before and after, so we know the job is actually done.</p>

<h3>My LG dryer d80 code came back after the vent was cleaned. What's wrong?</h3>
<p>Two possibilities. If it came back within a few weeks, the vent wasn't fully cleared or has a section of flexible foil duct that's partially collapsed — it needs to be replaced with rigid metal. If it came back immediately after a confirmed clear vent, the Flow Sense thermistor sensor may be faulty and reading incorrectly even when the vent is clear. We test both scenarios on callbacks.</p>

<h3>Will the flow sense error damage my dryer if I ignore it?</h3>
<p>Yes — continued operation with d90 or d95 overheats the heating element and will blow the thermal fuse. That turns a $150 vent cleaning into a $280–350 fuse replacement plus the cleaning. On gas dryers, sustained overheating also stresses the igniter and gas valve coils over time.</p>

<h3>Can you come today?</h3>
<p>Yes — call (323) 990-7550. Same-day service across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County, typically 2–4 hours from your call.</p>

